  "text": "Denote by S n (µ) = {i : 1 ≤ i ≤ n, µ i ̸ = 0} the set of all non-zero components of µ. We focus on the case of sparse signals when S n (µ) constitutes a very small share of n; throughout this paper it is assumed that S n (µ) ≤ n 1−β for all n large enough and some β from (0, 1/3). Since it is not known beforehand which components of µ are not zero, the value of loss function (in the sense of (7) below) 236 ANDREY ORDIN in model (1) exceeds n 1−β . Moreover, reasonably precise estimations of the set S n (µ) require additional assumptions on the vector µ (see, e.g., [CITATION_1] ). On the other hand, under adaptive sampling these assumptions may be significantly relaxed. We will restrict our attention to the signals µ from the set",
